    72	
    73	So Yair’s reading is correct: `cat-` belongs to the category beat; `advcap-` and `advfreq-` belong to the two advanced beats. The variant prefixes (`g…`, `h…`, `w…`) are likewise beat/variant namespaces. They do **not** select a checker or cause code to run.
    74	
    75	### 2. `eval:verbatim-opener`: does any implementation exist?
    76	
    77	**No.** A full text search of the render repo (excluding generated outputs), `/home/ggvoice/gg-ground/gg-mvp`, and `/home/ggvoice/gg-spec` found the ID only in the render registry. There is no harness evaluator, test, script, or runtime comparison that asserts an output exactly equals the declared opener.
    78	
    79	Closest nearby code is not enough:
    80	
    81	- `scripts/render-link-integrity-check.mjs:90` verifies only that a declared clip file exists.
    82	- `/home/ggvoice/gg-ground/gg-mvp/api/_lib/__tests__/beat-context-parity.test.ts:88` only rejects em dashes and gesture words in configured opener strings.
    83	- Prompt instructions can request a verbatim opener, but an LLM instruction is not enforceable verification.
    84	
    85	### 3. `tool-contract-check`: is the runtime `allowedTools` gate real, and does the render claim match it?
    86	
    87	**Yes, the runtime gate is real—but it is only a partial implementation of the render claim.**
    88	
    89	1. Per-screen `allowedTools` are held in `BEAT_CONTEXTS` and can be replaced from a generated flow export in `/home/ggvoice/gg-ground/gg-mvp/api/_lib/llm/onboarding/beatContexts.ts:605`.
    90	2. `getOnboardingTools()` filters the global onboarding tool definitions to those names in `/home/ggvoice/gg-ground/gg-mvp/api/_lib/llm/onboarding/registry.ts:21`.
    91	3. The live route gives the model only that list at `/home/ggvoice/gg-ground/gg-mvp/api/llm/[...path].ts:652–670`, and belt-and-suspenders rejects any attempted name outside the set at `:927–937` before dispatch.
    92	
    93	The mismatch is material: `beatsSource.ts`’s `bible.allowedTools`/`rulesCode` prose is not consumed by that API path. The app uses its own `beatContexts.ts` plus generated `onboarding_combined.json`. Therefore a render beat can claim “only X and Y are callable” while the live app gate has a different list, without a test joining the two sources. The app parity test validates the **generated flow export ↔ app context/tool names**, not **render registry ↔ live gate**.
    94	
    95	## Shortest path from aspirational name to enforcement
    96	
    97	- `id-alias-check` — write a script that extracts each alias surface from `beatsSource.ts`, enforces uniqueness/mapping against the app’s generated step/route data, and add it to CI.
    98	- `reveal-timing-check` — make reveal gates structured data, then assert every reveal references a valid preceding event/clip and test the renderer’s event sequence.
    99	- `eval:edge-walk` — define a machine-readable transition graph and run a deterministic traversal over all branch/variant edges.
   100	- `eval:no-read-options` — record/fixture model outputs per option-bearing beat and fail when option labels are spoken without an explicit request condition.
   101	- `decisions-coverage-check` — give each product decision a canonical ID, require each applicable beat to declare it, and assert no decision is uncovered or stale.
   102	- `eval:verbatim-opener` — store canonical opener text/clip transcript and compare actual emitted opening event/audio transcript byte-for-byte (or an explicit normalized policy).
   103	- `eval:no-platitudes` — define a reviewed prohibited-pattern evaluator plus fixture outputs; treat it as a heuristic quality gate, not absolute semantic truth.
   104	- `eval:silent-after-pick` — instrument selection and assistant/audio events and assert no speech event occurs in the defined post-pick window.
   105	
   106	For the six partial IDs, close the gap rather than renaming them: bind `advance-gate-check`, `tool-contract-check`, `eval:parity-walk`, and `persistence-contract-check` to the render-exported contract; expand `component-registry-check` to actual component/props validation; and make `audio-ownership-check` assert declared runtime/ownership rather than merely a file’s existence.
   107	
   108	## Trust headline
   109	
   110	**1 of 15 enforcement IDs is real today, 6 are partial, and 8 are aspirational names.** The system contains meaningful real code around tool exposure, advancement, persistence, and link integrity. But only link integrity is honestly represented by its `enforcedBy` name today. The shortest trust-building move is to make `enforcedBy` machine-resolved: every ID must point to a runnable checker/test, have a documented invocation, and fail CI when its declared contract is violated. Until then, these IDs should be presented as intended controls, not proof of enforcement.

